04758nam a22006735i 9780520910218DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20211992cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209102187 a10.1525/97805209102182doi  a(DE-B1597)544211  a(OCoLC)1286808743  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0020102bisacsh04a938.8qOCoLC1 aBirge, Darice E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTopographical and Architectural Studies :bThe Sacred Square, the Xenon and the Bath /cDarice E. Birge, Stephen G. Miller, Lynn H. Kraynak.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b1 frontisp.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExcavations at Nemea ;v100tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tList of Illustrations -- tSelected Bibliography and Abbreviations -- tAbbreviations Used in the Text and Catalogue -- tElevations, Grid References, and Measurements -- tIntroduction -- tChapter I: The Sacred Square -- tChapter II: The Xenon -- tChapter III: The Bath -- tCatalogue of Artifacts -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn classical antiquity, beginning in 573 B.C., Nemea hosted international athletic competitions like those at Olympia, Delphi, and Isthmia; the games at the four sites constituted the Panhellenic cycle, and the victors were the most famous athletes of antiquity. Nemea was never a city-state but served as a religious and athletic festival center where the Greek world assembled every two years under a flag of truce. Excavations sponsored by the University of California, Berkeley since 1974 have revealed many details of Nemea's history. These discoveries, together with ancient literary and epigraphic sources, form the basis of a new and sharply defined picture of the Nemean Games. This first volume in a projected series of nine documents the excavations of the Sacred Square, the Xenon (Guest House), and the Bath. In her chapter on the Sacred Square, Darice Birge gives us a full publication of the Long Altar of Zeus and other monuments, as well as the first recognized remains of a Sacred Grove from antiquity. Lynn Kraynak presents the findings on the Xenon, one of the few ancient hotels to have been recognized and the only one to be fully studied. Finally, Stephen Miller reports on the Nemean Bath, the earliest Greek bath known. Nemea I presents all of these findings together with associated material--state plans, photographs, and drawings of reconstructed monuments--making this volume important not only to scholars interested in the specific aspects of the excavations, but also to teachers who will make use of the reconstructions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aAncient Archaeology. 4aAncient History. 4aancient Greek history. 4aantiquity. 4aclassical antiquity. 4ahistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh1 aBirge, Darice E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraynak, Lynn H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKraynak, Lynn H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Stephen G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMiller, Stephen G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052007027140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091021840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520910218423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520910218/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California